The '''little gull''' ('''''Hydrocoloeus minutus''''') is a species of gull belonging to the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Laridae]] which is mainly found in the [[Palearctic]] with some small colonies in North America. It breeds on freshwater lakes and marshes, and spends winters at sea. It is the smallest species of gull in the world, and the only species in the [[monospecific genus]] '''''Hydrocoloeus'''''.

==Taxonomy==
The little gull was first formally [[Species description|described]] as ''Larus minutus'' in 1776 by the German [[ornithologist]] [[Peter Simon Pallas]] with its [[Type locality (biology)|type locality]] given as [[Beryozovo, Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug|Berezovo]], [[Tobolsk]] in Siberia. In 1829, [[Johann Jakob Kaup]] proposed the genus '''''Hydrocoloeus''''' for this species, and [[George Robert Gray]] later formally designated ''Larus minutus'' as the [[type species]] of the genus.<ref name =AOU>{{cite book |title=Checklist of North American Birds |edition=6 |author=American Ornithologists' Union (AOU) |year=1983 |pages=212–223 |publisher=The Union |isbn=978-0-943610-32-0 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/107977#page/247/mode/1up}}</ref> Kaup had also included ''Larus plumbiceps'' Meyer, 1822 in his genus ''Hydrocoloeus''; this is a [[synonymy (biology)|synonym]] of [[grey-headed gull|''Chroicocephalus cirrocephalus'']] (grey-headed gull).<ref name="Wilms">{{cite web | last=Wilms | first=Herman | title=Hydrocoloeus | website=www.wnve.nl | url=https://www.wnve.nl/nl/genus/383-g-hydrocoloeus | language=nl | access-date=2025-03-24}}</ref> ''Hydrocoloeus minutus'' is the binomial accepted for this species and it is classified in the family Laridae, the gulls and terns, in the order [[Charadriiformes]].<ref name=Avibase/><ref name= IOC>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/bow/gulls/ |title=Noddies, skimmers, gulls, terns, skuas, auks |access-date=15 August 2023 |work=IOC World Bird List v13.2 |publisher=[[International Ornithologists' Union]] |editor1=Frank Gill |editor2=David Donsker |editor3=Pamela Rasmussen |name-list-style=&}}</ref>

Within the Laridae, its closest relative is [[Ross's gull]] ''Rhodostethia rosea'';<ref name="Černý">{{cite journal | last=Černý | first=David | last2=Natale | first2=Rossy | title=Comprehensive taxon sampling and vetted fossils help clarify the time tree of shorebirds (Aves, Charadriiformes) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=177 | date=2022 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2022.107620 | doi-access=free | article-number=107620 | url=https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2021/07/16/2021.07.15.452585.full.pdf | access-date=2025-03-24}}</ref> some authors have even included Ross's gull in ''Hydrocoloeus'' rather than giving it its own genus,<ref>{{cite web | last=Römhild | first=Markus | title=Der Erstnachweis der Rosenmöwe ''Hydrocoloeus roseus'' für Bayern | url=https://www.zobodat.at/pdf/Avifaunistik-Bayern_4_0011-0014.pdf | access-date=2025-03-24}}</ref> but this has not been accepted by any of the major ornithological authorities.

===Etymology===
The genus name ''Hydrocoloeus'' means "water jackdaw", from [[Ancient Greek]] {{Transliteration|el|hydro}}, water, and {{Transliteration|el|koloios}}, a [[western jackdaw|jackdaw]]; Kaup, in naming the genus, compared the little gull to other gulls as he then went on to compare his new genus ''[[Coloeus]]'' for jackdaws to crows;<ref name="Kaup">{{cite book | last=Kaup | first=J. J. | title=Skizzirte Entwickelungs-Geschichte und natürliches System der europäischen Thierwelt: Erster Theil welcher die Vogelsäugethiere und Vögel nebst Andeutung der Entstehung der letzteren aus Amphibien enthält | publisher=In commission bei Carl Wilhelm Leske | publication-place=Darmstadt | year=1829 | doi=10.5962/bhl.title.63915 | doi-access=free | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/itempdf/129856 | access-date=2025-03-24 | pages=113–114}}</ref> Kaup had a personal theory of equivalence between members of different groups of birds based on their relative sizes.<ref name="Wilms"/> The specific {{lang|la|minutus}} is [[Latin]] for "small".<ref name=job>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url= https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher= Christopher Helm | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages= [https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n196 196], 256}}</ref>

==Description==
The little gull has a body length of {{cvt|24|to|28|cm}} and a wing span of {{cvt|62|to|69|cm}},<ref name = Collins>{{cite book |author1=[[Lars Svensson (ornithologist)|Lars Svensson]] |author2=[[Killian Mullarney]] |author3=[[Dan Zetterström]] |year=2023 |title=Collins Bird Guide |edition=3 |pages=196–197 |isbn=978-0-00-854745-5 |publisher=William Collins}}</ref> making it the smallest gull species in the world.<ref name=eBird>{{cite web |url=https://ebird.org/species/litgul |title=Little Gull |access-date=15 August 2023 |publisher=eBird}}</ref> The adults in breeding plumage have a black hood, dark red bill, bright red legs, and sometimes a rosy flush to the underside. In non-breeding plumage the adults have a black cap and spot on the ear, white underparts, a black bill and the red on the legs is duller. In all plumages the adults have a pale grey back and upperwings with white [[Flight feather|primaries]] contrasting with very dark grey underwing. The juveniles have large areas of blackish colour on the back and head and in flight they have a dark "w" pattern on the upperwings with white underwings. By their first winter the head and body are similar to those of an adult but the upperwing pattern is retained. By their second year they have become very similar to the adults but have some black primary feathers.<ref name=Collins/>

==Distribution==
The little gull has a wide Palearctic distribution breeding from northern Scandinavia and the eastern [[Baltic Sea]] to eastern Siberia. They also breed in North America around the [[Great Lakes]]. It is a migratory species which winters along the coasts of Europe as far south as the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], [[Black Sea|Black]] and [[Caspian Sea]]s.<ref name = Birdlife>{{cite web | publisher= BirdLife International |year=2023 |title=Species factsheet: ''Hydrocoloeus minutus'' |url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/species/factsheet/little-gull-hydrocoloeus-minutus |access-date=15 August 2023}}</ref> They are uncommon in the western Pacific.<ref name= Brazil>{{cite book |author=[[Mark Brazil]] |year=2009 |title=Birds of East Asia China, Taiwan, Korea, Japan and Russia |page=214 |publisher=Princeton |isbn=978-0-691-13926-5}}</ref> In North America they winter along the Atlantic coasts in small numbers,<ref name = Birdlife/> as far south as the Carolinas.<ref>{{cite book | last1=Potter | first1=Eloise F. | last2=Parnell | first2=James F. | last3=Teulings | first3=Robert P. | last4=Davis | first4=Ricky | title=Birds of the Carolinas | publisher=UNC Press Books | date=2015-12-01 | isbn=978-1-4696-2565-2}}</ref> In the early 21st Century non-breeding birds have summered in western Europe in increasing numbers and in 2016 they successfully nested for the first time in [[Great Britain]] at the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|RSPB]] reserve at [[Loch of Strathbeg]] reserve in [[Aberdeenshire]];<ref name = RBA>{{cite web | url = http://www.rarebirdalert.co.uk/v2/Content/RSPB_Worlds_smallest_gull_breed_in_Scotland_for_the_first_time.aspx?s_id=886794278 | title = World's smallest gull breeding in Scotland for the first time | access-date = 6 August 2017 | publisher = Rare Bird Alert}}</ref> they returned for a few days in May 2017, but did not breed again.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Holling |first1=Mark |title=Rare breeding birds in the UK in 2017 |journal=British Birds |date=2019 |volume=112 |issue=12 |page=737 }}</ref>

==Habitat==
The little gull nests in areas of dense vegetation where there are [[Aquatic plant|emergent]] or plants with floating leaves in shallow freshwater bodies, slow-moving rivers, marshes and bogs, occasionally using costal lagoons or other brackish water habitats. When it is migrating this species is coastal but may be found inland in some conditions. They also winter on the coast where there are sand and mud substrates and at river mouths and even out to sea. They may be attracted to sewage outfalls.<ref name =Birdlife/>

==Biology==
The little gull is a migratory species with separate breeding and wintering ranges. They typically arrive at their breeding areas from late-April up to late May and start to move away from the breeding areas from the middle of July. Laying eggs begins in mid-June and they commonly nest among other species of gull and tern to form mixed colonies, although some pairs will nest singly away from colonies. Away from the breeding areas this is a sociable species and feeds and loafs in flocks. These flocks can be very large and may number of thousands of birds if bad weather forces them into sheltered waters. The nests are situated on the ground or on the water, floating on leaves and fixed to emergent vegetation and are spaced at distances of {{cvt|1|to|1.5|m}} from each other in colonies.<ref name =Birdlife/>

Breeding birds are insectivores and feed on a variety of insects caught on the wing close to the water and in winter the diet is dominated by small fish and marine invertebrates.<ref name = Birdlife/>

